<HL>
   Bank-Broker CD Yields
   Climbed in Latest Week
</HL>
<DATE>
09/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<IN>
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
BANKS (BNK)
SECURITIES (SCR)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Yields on certificates of deposit at major
banks and brokerage firms rose in the week ended Tuesday.
   Average yields on small-denomination CDs sold directly by
banks edged up slightly. The average yield on a six-month CD
rose to 7.39% from 7.37%, according to an 18-bank national
survey by Banxquote Money Markets, a New York information
service. Meanwhile, the average yield on a five-year consumer
CD remained at 7.91%.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Up significantly more were average yields on
small-denomination CDs sold by leading broker dealers. The
average yield on a six-month broker-sold CD rose to 7.92%
from 7.75%, according to Banxquote. The average yield for a
one-year broker-sold CD rose to 8.02% from 7.74%, while the
average for five-year maturities rose to 8.70% from 8.35%.
   Meanwhile, average yields for large-denomination CDs,
which typically require deposits of $90,000 or more, were
also up. The average yield on a one-year "jumbo" CD rose to
7.83% from 7.73%, while the average for a five-year maturity
rose to 8.31% from 8.27%.
</TEXT>
