   The following were among yesterday's offerings and
pricings in U.S. and non-U.S. capital markets, with terms and
syndicate manager, as compiled by Dow Jones Capital Markets
Report.
                                                                                                       

                         CORPORATE
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   Coastal Corp. -- $400 million of debt securities in a
two-part offering priced through underwriters at Lehman
Brothers. The first part, $250 million of 10 3/8% notes due
Oct. 1, 2000, was priced at 99 7/8 to yield 10.395%, a spread
of 137.5 basis points above the Treasury's 10-year note. The
second part, $150 million of 10 3/4% debentures due Oct. 1,
2010, was priced at 99.59 to yield 10.80%, a spread of 165
basis points above the Treasury's 30-year bond. The issue is
rated Baa-3 by Moody's Investors Service Inc. and
triple-B-minus by Standard &amp; Poor's Corp.
                                                                                                       

                         MUNICIPAL
                                                                                                       

   Washington Public Power Supply System -- $250 million of
revenue refunding bonds, Nuclear Project No. 1, Series 1990C,
priced by a Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co. group to yield from 6.60% in
1992 to 8.04% in 2017. Current interest serial bonds are
priced to yield from 6.60% in 1992 to 7.80% in 2003.
Uninsured 7% current interest serial bonds maturing in 1995
are priced to yield 7.10%. There are $25.2 million of 7 3/4%
term bonds priced at 99 1/2 to yield 7.80% in 2008 and $65
million of 8% term bonds priced at 99 1/2 to yield 8.04% in
2017. The issue has been rated double-A by Moody's, S&amp;P and
Fitch's Investors Service, except for bonds due in 2000 and
2008, which are insured and triple-A-rated.
   California Public Works Board -- $165.1 million of lease
revenue bonds, 1990 Series A, priced by a Morgan Stanley &amp;
Co. group to yield from 6.00% in 1991 to 7.55% in 2010. The
issue has been rated double-A by S&amp;P and Fitch's and
conditional double-A by Moody's. Term bonds have a 7% coupon
and are priced to 7.55% to 2010.
   Clark County School District, Nev. -- $120 million of
school improvement limited tax revenue bonds, via
underwriters led by First Boston Corp. Yields were
tentatively set at 6.10% in 1991 to 7.70% in 2010. The First
Boston group won the $47 million of Group 3 bonds, which
comprises two term bond maturities, priced to yield 7.65% in
2007 and 7.70% in 2010. A Lehman Brothers group won $40
million of Group 1 bonds, which were priced to yield from
6.10% in 1991 to 7.25% in 2000. A Prudential-Bache Capital
Funding group won the $33 million of Group 2 bonds, which
were priced to yield from 7.20% in 2001 to 7.55% in 2005.
Group 1 and 2 bonds are insured and rated triple-A by Moody's
and S&amp;P. The Group 3 term bonds have been rated single-A-1 by
Moody's and single-A-plus by S&amp;P.
                                                                                                       

                         MORTGAGES
                                                                                                       

   Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. -- $300 million of Remic
mortgage securities offered in eight classes by Nomura
Securities International. The offering, Series FHLMC Gold
1011, is backed by Freddie Mac 9 1/2% gold participation
certificates. Among fixed-rate classes for which details were
available, spreads were 80 basis points over the Treasury's
when-issued two-year note for securities with an average life
of 2.44 years, 103 basis points over five-year Treasurys on
those with an average life of 5.778 years and 103 basis
points over seven-year Treasurys for the class with an
average life of 7 3/4 years. Class D floats at 75 basis
points over the one-month London Interbank offered rate, and
Class F floats at 90 basis points over one-month Libor. Both
those classes have an 11.50% cap. The collateral has a
weighted average coupon rate of 10.125% and weighted average
remaining term to maturity of 29.17 years.
   Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. -- $300 million of Remic
mortgage securities offered in 12 classes by Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc. The offering, Series FHLMC Gold 1012, is
backed by Freddie Mac 8% gold participation certificates with
a weighted average coupon rate of 9.05% and weighted average
remaining term to maturity of 25.58 years. Price and yield
data weren't immediately available.
                                                                                                       

