<HL>
   Defense Spending
   By Soviets Fell 5%,
   Pentagon Reports
   ----
   By Walter S. Mossberg
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST
</CO>
<IN>
AEROSPACE (ARO)
NUCLEAR POWER, FUEL (NUK)
</IN>
<GV>
DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Pentagon said the Soviet Union cut
overall defense spending last year by 4% to 5% and slashed
production of tanks, ammunition, helicopters and other
weapons.
   Nevertheless, Defense Secretary Dick Cheney, in releasing
the department's annual review of the Soviet military, warned
that the Soviet Union remains a military threat that must be
countered.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The ninth edition of Soviet Military Power reported a cut
of between 6% and 7% in weapons procurement spending, a
halving of tank production to 1,700 from 3,500, and lesser
cuts in the output of fighter planes, bombers, artillery and
other important weapons. It also disclosed a "dramatic
decrease" in Soviet space launches and predicted that Moscow
will scrap as many as 450 navy ships by 1996 and cut 80,000
sailors from its navy.
   The slick book still features photos of menacing Red Army
weapons, just as it has since it was first issued by the
Reagan administration to gather public support for the
military buildup of the 1980s.
   But this year, the book also included photos of Soviet
troops leaving Eastern Europe, Soviet missiles being
destroyed to comply with arms-control treaties, and Soviet
bombers whose tails had been cut off to make them unusable.
   The report, however, repeatedly noted that in some weapons
categories, especially strategic nuclear weapons, Moscow is
continuing to build strength and that even reduced output
levels for items such as tanks still top Western production
rates. It also stressed that the Soviets still field the
world's largest military force.
   "What it does not reveal, no matter how much we might wish
it," said Mr. Cheney, "is an eviscerated Soviet force
structure and an evaporating threat . . . The Soviet Union
remains an enormous military superpower."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900926-0078
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900926-0078.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Tax Report:
   A Special Summary and Forecast
   Of Federal and State Tax
   Developments
   ----
   By Scott R. Schmedel
</HL>
<DATE>
09/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<CO>
   TAXES EUROP FREST AFRIC FORGN LABOR
</CO>
<IN>
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
MORTGAGES, MORTGAGE BANKERS, MORTGAGE-BACKED SECURITIES (MOR)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
REAL ESTATE INVESTMENTS (REA)
RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)
DIVERSIFIED FINANCIAL SERVICES, FANNIE MAE, FREDDIE MAC (FIS)
</IN>
<GV>
INTERNAL REVENUE SERVICE (IRS)
CONGRESS (CNG)
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   BUSINESSES PROTEST plans to deny deductions for interest
on their tax debts.
   The 1986 tax act eliminated personal deductions of
interest on tax underpayments. On Sept. 6, Rep. Stark (D.,
Calif.), calling for equal treatment, entered a bill to deny
such deductions to corporations. To businesses' dismay, his
proposal has popped up among items tentatively accepted by
both Democrat and Republican budget negotiators, who say it
may raise $4.5 billion over five years. So major trade groups
-- including manufacturers, bankers and doctors -- are
mounting an attack on the plan.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Interest is an ordinary and necessary business expense,
they say, and often stems from protracted good-faith disputes
over complex law. The corporate Tax Executives Institute
calls the proposal "gimmickry" meant to force corporations to
rush to pay interest before it takes effect in 1991. Andre
Fogarasi of Arthur Andersen &amp; Co., CPAs, says the proposal
would disrupt audits and the newly revised penalty system.
   For individuals and corporations, interest paid on overdue
tax refunds would remain taxable under the proposal.
                                                                                                       

   HE LOST FAITH in conversion after this foreign-exchange
loss.
   A U.S. citizen we'll call Cosmo bought a place abroad in
1986 for local currency -- let's say 95,000 clams, equal then
to $95,000. He financed it with an 85,000-clam mortgage and
made it his home. Cosmo sold his home in 1989 for 142,000
clams and used 85,000 to pay off the mortgage, leaving a gain
taxable on his U.S. return. On that return, he must convert
clams into dollars at the rates in effect at the time of the
transactions. Trouble is, the dollar fell 5% against the clam
between 1986 and 1989.
   In clams, Cosmo did all right. But in dollars -- just on
his return -- he paid $4,474 more to retire the loan than he
borrowed, so he has an exchange loss. Naturally, he wants to
deduct the loss from his sale gain. But IRS Revenue Ruling
90-79 says he can't: A mortgage transaction is treated
separately from a home purchase and sale. Tax law limits
personal-loss deductions to those from a business, an
income-producing activity, or a casualty. Losses on home
mortgages don't qualify. (A gain on selling a home is
taxable; a loss isn't deductible.)
                                                                                                       

   OLD IRONSIDES the boat isn't, but the IRS can't sell it as
perishable goods.
   On June 1, the IRS seized a $72,500 cutter from Gerald A.
Galusha, a confessed marijuana grower, fearing he would try
to evade an alleged $223,000 in back taxes. The IRS put the
47-foot, 24-year-old sailboat in dry dock in Seattle and
planned its sale on Aug. 1 if Galusha didn't post a $72,500
bond. But he turned to the Tax Court: While a case is pending
there, the IRS may sell seized assets only on certain
conditions. One is that the property is perishable. The IRS
claimed it could meet the terms.
   The IRS said the wood hull would deteriorate rapidly in
dry dock or even in the water without extensive maintenance.
It also argued that maintenance costs would reduce sale
proceeds and that the boat's value would drop if a sale were
delayed. Now Judge Gerber has granted Galusha's plea to stay
a sale pending the outcome of the tax case. "Perishable"
means rapid decay, the judge said, yet proper care in the
water should preserve the boat for years.
   Also, the IRS failed to show the boat was losing value or
that maintenance would be too costly, the judge added.
                                                                                                       

   AFFORDABLE-HOUSING aid for the poor in metropolitan areas
now qualifies for Missouri state-income-tax credits of as
much as 55% of eligible expenses. Total annual credits are
limited to $2 million in the first year, but the ceiling
rises eventually to $10 million.
                                                                                                       

   INCOME-TAX TREATIES with West Germany, Spain, Finland,
Tunisia, India, and Indonesia were ratified by the Senate. It
also agreed to a treaty to share tax data with certain
nations in the Organization for Economic Cooperation and
Development.
                                                                                                       

   A NEW ESTATE-TAX RETURN, Form 706, has been delayed again
at least until mid-October. Due first in August and then this
month, it will replace the 1988 version and reflects several
changes in the law.
                                                                                                       

   A GETTY SON finds a way without a will to get $10 million
tax-free.
   J. Ronald Getty, eldest son of J. Paul Getty, felt
short-changed when the billionaire left most of his wealth to
the Getty Museum in 1976. Ronald Getty sued the museum,
claiming his father reneged on a promised bequest, and
settled for $10 million in 1980. To him, the cash was in lieu
of a bequest; he didn't report it on his return. But to the
IRS, it was ordinary income, taxable in 1980 at the 70% top
rate; and in 1988, the Tax Court agreed the money replaced
lost income, not inherited property.
   Ronald Getty appealed. Now the ninth-circuit appeals court
has upheld his stand. While the Tax Court saw ambiguity in
the facts, appellate Judge Thompson says a preponderance of
the evidence shows that Getty sued the museum to reclaim a
lost bequest. Thus, the settlement payment should be treated
as tax-free property, not income.
   The Tax Court's 1988 ruling noted that Getty had spent $2
million in legal fees in suing the museum.
                                                                                                       

   BRIEFS: The non-profit NCAA isn't taxable on advertising
income from basketball-tourney programs, the 10th-circuit
appeals court says, reversing the Tax Court. . . . Fighting
intensified audits of small pension plans, the American
Society of Pension Actuaries wins a court order directing the
IRS to disclose documents on which a $666 million tax-revenue
estimate was based.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900926-0077
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900926-0077.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   U.S.-Built Car, Truck Sales Fall 5.7%
   In Good Showing From Strong '89 Level
   ----
   By Neal Templin
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12
</SO>
<CO>
   GM F C HMC TOYOY NSANY J.MZD J.MOT J.FJH J.IZM
</CO>
<IN>
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
</IN>
<LP>
   DETROIT -- Sales of domestically built cars and trucks
fell 5.7% in mid-September from a strong year-ago period. The
drop was surprisingly small given the soaring gasoline prices
and a slowing economy.
   Some of the strength in the market, analysts said, came
from buyers snapping up 1990-model cars before the
higher-priced 1991 models hit the showroom. "Even skittish
consumers are finding the model year close-out bargains too
good to pass up," said Thomas Webb, chief economist for the
National Automobile Dealers Association. The 1991 model year
begins Monday.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The seasonally adjusted annual selling rate for passenger
cars was a robust 7.8 million vehicles, compared with a hot
8.3 million annual rate a year ago and a 7.1 million rate in
early September.
   Overall, the 10 domestic car makers sold 322,216 vehicles
in the second 10 days of September, down 5.7% from the 1989
period. Domestic truck sales fell 10.6%, but domestic car
sales were much stronger, declining only 2.6%.
   The drop in truck sales, which in recent years have been
more robust than car sales, indicates that some consumers are
nervous about rising gasoline prices. But some models of
large cars continue to sell well, showing that there hasn't
yet been a wholesale shift toward smaller, fuel-efficient
cars.
   "You still get some people who don't care about the
mileage," said Roy Watson, sales manager of Forest Lake
Chrysler and Forest Lake Ford in Minnesota. "They just drive
what they want to drive."
   The Japanese auto makers continued to post strong gains in
sales of vehicles produced in their U.S. assembly plants.
Nissan Motor Co. and Mazda Motor Corp. each more than doubled
sales of domestically assembled vehicles from the year-ago
period.
   Not all Japanese auto makers fared as well. Mitsubishi
Motors Corp. sales of domestically produced cars fell 6.8%
from a year ago. Mitsubishi said it had a generous
dealer-incentive program running this time last year, and
that the company also is running short of its sporty Eclipse
models.
   But economic and political uncertainties also are taking
their toll, the company conceded. Showroom traffic is off 40%
from two months ago, said Richard S. Recchia, head of
Mitsubishi's U.S. sales arm. "A lot of people have deferred
the decision to buy until they see what will happen with the
economy and the Middle East," Mr. Recchia added.
   Ford Motor Co. put in the strongest performance of the
U.S. Big Three car makers. Ford's domestic car sales fell
7.3% while its domestic truck sales were down 7.9%.
   Ford's efforts to revive sales of its Escort subcompact
car appear to be working. Escort sales, which sagged earlier
in the year despite the introduction of a revamped model,
were up 11.2% from a year ago. Sales have been mounting ever
since Ford placed consumer incentives on the car in August.
   General Motors Corp. posted a 9.6% drop in total vehicles
sales, including a 16.3% drop in domestic truck sales.
Domestic car sales were down 6.4% while sales of GM's
imported cars, which included its fuel-efficient Geo line,
rose 10.4%.
   Chrysler Corp., hurting all year, continued to struggle in
mid-September. Domestic car sales dropped 12.1% from a year
ago, while domestic truck sales -- including Jeeps and
minivans -- declined 18.5%.
   ---
