<HL>
   America West Says
   Talks on Pan Am
   Shuttle Continue
   ----
   By Bridget O'Brian
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   PN AWAL F.ABI U.GPA
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
AIRLINES (AIR)
AEROSPACE (ARO)
</IN>
<LP>
   America West Airlines said it is continuing talks with Pan
Am Corp. over the possible acquisition of Pan Am's East Coast
shuttle but that an agreement hasn't been reached.
   The Phoenix, Ariz., carrier also said it is still
negotiating a possible lease of more than 100 Airbus
Industrie A320 jets in a transaction that would involve
financial support from manufacturers and leasing companies.
No agreement has been reached in those talks, America West
said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In a statement yesterday, America West's president,
Michael J. Conway, declined to say what price is under
discussion for the Pan Am shuttle but termed recent public
speculation "premature and not well founded." A spokesman for
New York-based Pan Am declined to comment.
   When Pan Am announced the shuttle was for sale, it said it
hoped to get about $250 million for it. Since then, however,
conditions in the airline industry have worsened
substantially.
   Pan Am put the shuttle up for sale in late May, not long
after cash-strapped developer and executive Donald Trump put
out feelers to determine how much money he might get from
selling the competing Trump Shuttle. Financially ailing Pan
Am has been selling assets and reorganizing to try to raise
cash.
   Last week, Pan Am Chairman Thomas Plaskett told Wall
Street analysts he expected to sell the shuttle by year end
but that he didn't expect any sale to actually be final until
1991. Mr. Plaskett also said the airline will cut 8.6% of its
work force, slash its 1991 capacity by 7.5% and switch to
smaller, more efficient jets from Boeing Co.'s fuel-guzzling
747s on several of its trans-Atlantic routes.
   America West -- with hubs in Phoenix and Las Vegas and
with mostly Southwestern routes -- has for years sought a
toehold in the lucrative New York and Washington markets.
Owning a Northeast shuttle could provide that kind of access.
Last year, America West gamely tried to outbid Mr. Trump for
the Eastern Airlines shuttle after Eastern took refuge in
bankruptcy court. Negotiating right up to the deadline,
America West ultimately couldn't come up with the financing.
   It's unclear how America West might finance the
acquisition of the Pan Am shuttle, which like the Trump
operation connects New York to Boston and Washington. A
person familiar with the talks said the proposed aircraft
deal calls for America West to get $200 million in financial
aid from Guinness Peat Aviation -- the company that would
lease America West 26 of the A320s -- and from International
Aero Engines, a consortium of five engine manufacturers.
Airbus itself wouldn't provide any of the money, the person
said.
   The person said this financial aid could help underwrite
the purchase of the shuttle or help meet the costs of
introducing Airbus planes into the all-Boeing America West
fleet. The person said the two potential transactions aren't
dependent on each other.
   Half of the 100 A320s involved were ordered originally by
Pan Am. But in late 1988, Pan Am sold those delivery
positions to now-defunct Braniff Airlines. Braniff added
options on 50 more jets.
   Braniff folded last fall, leaving ownership of the planes
and delivery positions the subjects of bankruptcy court
litigation. A few A320 jets that were delivered have been
parked at the Las Vegas airport. Those and the remainder of
the Braniff order form the core of the transaction under
discussion between America West and Airbus.
   ---
   Asra Q. Nomani contributed to this article.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900926-0064
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900926-0064.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Senate Supporters of Fuel Economy Bill
   Lose Vote, Dooming Measure This Year
   ----
   By Rose Gutfeld
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   JAPAN TOYOY J.SUZ HMC G.VOW J.DHM
</CO>
<IN>
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
ENVIRONMENT (ENV)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY (EPA)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Lawmakers pushing legislation to tighten
fuel-economy rules for cars lost a procedural vote in the
Senate, dooming the bill's chances for this year.
   Separately, the Environmental Protection Agency released
data showing that nine of the 10 most fuel-efficient
1991-model cars are made in Japan.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Senate supporters of the bill fell three votes short of
the 60 needed to cut off a filibuster by opponents. The vote
was 57-42. The measure was opposed by the administration and
the auto industry.
   The legislation, sponsored by Sen. Richard Bryan (D.,
Nev.), would require auto makers to increase the fuel
efficiency of their fleets 20% in the model year 1995 and 40%
by 2001.
   Among other administration efforts against the bill,
Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner two weeks ago called
a news conference to release studies asserting that the
measure would result in additional highway accidents and
deaths. And along with Energy Secretary James Watkins and
Environmental Protection Agency chief, William Reilly, Mr.
Skinner sent a letter opposing the measure to Senate leaders
this week.
   Sen. Bryan said in an interview that "the administration
really brought out its heavy artillery" to defeat the bill.
Nonetheless, he said the vote indicated considerable support
for tougher fuel-economy standards among lawmakers, and he
added that he looked forward "to waging a new battle" for the
bill next year.
   The auto makers were delighted by the Senate vote. A
spokesman for Toyota Motor Co. said, "It looks like the bill
is dead this year. We think {that is} great."
   The fuel-economy bill, once viewed largely as an
anti-pollution measure, gained new momentum as an oil-saving
proposal in the wake of the Mideast crisis. Proponents were
buoyed two weeks ago when they won an earlier procedural vote
by a wider margin than expected. Following that vote,
however, the White House stepped up its lobbying, which
helped to defeat yesterday's effort.
   Moreover, the bill's chances always were less certain in
the House, where it was pending before the House Energy and
Commerce Committee. Rep. John Dingell (D., Mich.), chairman
of that panel, is a longtime champion of the auto industry.
   The EPA rankings listed the subcompact Geo Metro XFI as
the most fuel-efficient car, at 53 miles per gallon for city
driving and 58 mpg on the highway. The car is made by Suzuki
and sold by General Motors Corp.
   Eight other Japanese-made cars and one from West Germany
rounded out the top-10 list. They are the Honda Civic CRX HF,
GEO Metro, Geo Metro LSI, Suzuki Swift, Honda Civic CRX HF,
Geo Metro LSI Con, Suzuki Swift, Daihatsu Charade and the
Volkswagen Jetta.
   The 10 least fuel-efficient cars all come from Europe,
with the Lamborghini DB132/Diablo topping the list. It gets
nine mpg in the city and 14 on the highway, the EPA said.
Purchasers of this model have to pay a $3,200 gas-guzzler
tax.
   The EPA figures on fuel efficiency have been released
annually since 1974.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
