   International Brief -- Banco Exterior de Espana:
   Banco Hispano Americano
   Merger Idea Under Study
</HL>
<DATE>
09/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP E.BEE E.BHA
</CO>
<IN>
BANKS (BNK)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   Banco Exterior de Espana confirmed it is studying a
possible merger with Banco Hispano Americano, but denied
talks between the two Spanish banks are under way.
   "We are not in negotiations, nor do we have a merger
plan," an Exterior official said, adding that combining the
state-owned bank with Hispano would imply privatization and
require government approval. A Hispano spokesman also
emphasized that a merger with Exterior isn't in the offing.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Exterior, Spain's seventh-largest bank, is 51.4%-owned by
the government. The state industrial holding company
Instituto Nacional de Industria and the Bank of Spain jointly
own a 13.94% stake in Exterior, and the financial services
company Factorex has an 8.42% interest. The rest is listed on
Spanish stock exchanges.
