<LP>
   ECONOMIC GROWTH SLOWED to a meager 0.4% in the second
quarter, revised data show, well below the 1.2% the
government estimated earlier. The White House continued to
insist that the economy isn't in a recession, even though the
revised figures don't reflect recent soaring oil prices.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   FDIC Chairman Seidman said he favors scaling back the
agency's insurance coverage for billions of dollars of
pension funds held in banks.
   ---
   MCA stock rose $19.50 to $54 a share on news that the
company has been in talks that could lead to its acquisition
by Matsushita, the Japanese consumer-electronics giant.
People close to the talks say the takeover price could be $80
to $90 a share, or $6.7 billion to $7.5 billion.
                                                                                                       

   The television networks hope Matshushita's talks with MCA
will help ease regulations that currently bar them from the
syndication market.
   ---
   Bush urged world leaders to ensure the success of trade
talks, saying they are threatened by an impasse over
agricultural subsidies. Earlier, EC farm ministers backed a
subsidy reform plan unacceptable to the U.S.
   ---
   Milken's lawyers asked a judge to sentence the former
Drexel junk-bond king to community service. Prosecutors
prepared to release new allegations painting Milken as a
major white-collar criminal.
   ---
   Fuel-economy legislation was doomed for the year when
lawmakers lost a Senate procedural vote.
   ---
   The administration is split over an Energy Department
proposal to sell a half million barrels of oil a day from the
Strategic Petroleum Reserve.
   ---
   Car and truck sales slipped 5.7% in mid-September, a
surprisingly strong performance in light of soaring gasoline
prices and a slowing economy.
   ---
   Stocks rebounded as oil prices fell. The Dow Jones
industrials advanced 32.67 points to 2485.64. Bonds rose.
   ---
   Bush appeared to be losing support from House Republican
Leader Michel for a cut in capital-gains taxes, a priority in
the budget talks.
   ---
   Citibank plans to lay off 100 workers in its
leveraged-lending unit, a senior bank official said.
   ---
   CS First Boston is quietly preparing to package $1.1
billion in troubled "bridge" loans and sell them.
   ---
   Elders IXL Ltd. posted a $1.08 billion fiscal-year loss,
biggest in Australian corporate history.
   ---
   Neil Bush should have told more about his ties to a
business partner for whom he tried to arrange a line of
credit, the former chief lending officer at Silverado S&amp;L
testified.
   ---
   Shearson Lehman must pay $800,000 in punitive damages to a
South Dakota investor, a jury decided.
   ---
   Reebok said it expects earnings to be lower for the third
quarter and flat for all 1990, despite strong sales for its
inflatable athletic shoe, the Pump.
   ---
   Donald Trump's bankers are expected today to demand that
he slash salaries and institute layoffs at the Trump Shuttle
in return for maintaining control of the troubled airline.
   ---
