<HL>
   Ex-Lawyer Pleads
   Guilty in Alleged
   Laundering Scheme
</HL>
<DATE>
09/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   BT
</CO>
<IN>
BANKS (BNK)
MAJOR MONEY CENTER BANKS (BAN)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Fred Stella, a former lawyer, pleaded guilty
to three felony counts in connection with an alleged
money-laundering scheme involving a former official of Bear,
Stearns &amp; Co.
   In federal court in Manhattan, Mr. Stella, 51 years old,
pleaded guilty to one count of conspiring to obstruct justice
and two counts of obstructing justice. He was indicted in May
along his brother Joseph Stella, 46, formerly head of Bear
Stearns' stock-loan department, and two others. Joseph Stella
resigned from Bear Stearns in April. Bear Stearns, a unit of
Bear Stearns Cos., wasn't involved in the alleged wrongdoing.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The four defendants were accused of laundering $1.7
million in checks that allegedly reflected the proceeds of
embezzled securities from Bankers Trust Co. and fees from
stock-loan transactions that others sought to avoid paying
taxes on. Bankers Trust is a unit of Bankers Trust New York
Corp.
   Fred Stella, of Brooklyn, is scheduled to be sentenced
Dec. 5 by federal Judge Charles Haight. The other defendents
are to go on trial Oct. 5 before Judge Haight.
   In addition to Joseph and Fred Stella, the indictment
named Roger C. Capozzi Sr. and Joseph A. Pontarelli. The
indictment accused Mr. Capozzi of cashing checks for Fred
Stella through a Brooklyn clothing-embroidery business. Mr.
Pontarelli was accused of cashing checks for Mr. Stella
through a Manhattan liquor store and check-cashing business.
</TEXT>
