<HL>
   Milken Called Qualified
   For `Domestic Peace Corps'
</HL>
<DATE>
09/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6
</SO>
<IN>
LAW AND LEGAL AFFAIRS (LAW)
SECURITIES (SCR)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   If Michael Milken's attorneys get their way, the former
$550 million-a-year man will be sentenced to work with the
Los Angeles Police Department to help inner-city youth.
   The attorneys proposed that Mr. Milken develop educational
and vocational programs to "combat the problems of drugs,
crime, unemployment and illiteracy threatening to destroy the
lives of inner-city youth in Los Angeles."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The proposal was based on a letter sent to U.S. District
Judge Kimba Wood by Daryl F. Gates, chief of police of Los
Angeles. Mr. Gates said in his letter that he met Mr. Milken
only once, several years ago, but that he believes Mr. Milken
would be uniquely qualified to establish a "domestic peace
corps" to help underprivileged children.
   In their sentencing memo, Mr. Milken's lawyers promised
that he would work, at a minimum, from 8 a.m. to 6 p.m.
daily, "and weekends {if the court desires.}"
   The memo noted that "Michael would not find this work
easy; nor would it be risk-free." Chief Gates proposed that
Mr. Milken work "not behind a comfortable corporate desk, but
in the communities targeted by the program."
   The government is expected to propose instead that Mr.
Milken serve a long prison term, and that its length be
dependent in part on his willingness to cooperate in the
government's continuing investigation of securities-related
crime.
   Mr. Milken's lawyers oppose any attempt to link the length
of the sentence to his cooperation, arguing that his plea
agreement made clear that he would cooperate only after his
sentencing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900926-0010
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900926-0010.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Timken to Upgrade
   Alloy Steel Plants
   At $170 Million Cost
</HL>
<DATE>
09/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   TKR
</CO>
<IN>
STEEL MANUFACTURERS (STL)
</IN>
<LP>
   CANTON, Ohio -- Timken Co., a bearings and steel producer,
said it will invest $170 million to improve its Canton alloy
steel production plants.
   The project is part of a $1 billion capital spending
program that Timken launched last year. The company has
detailed projects accounting for about one-third of the
money, including $210 million for its alloy and specialty
steels plants.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Timken said it will replace a bloom continuous caster at
its Harrison Steel plant here with new casting equipment.
Also, it will improve the small bar rolling mill and bar
finishing operations at the plant. Investment in the Harrison
facility, which makes alloy steels, including some used in
Timken's bearings, will total $110 million, Timken said.
   The company said it will spend $32 million at the adjacent
five-year-old Faircrest Steel Plant to improve productivity
and product quality. And it will spend $28 million to upgrade
computer systems that serve both facilities.
   Rust International Corp. was named project manager for the
work, Timken said. Completion dates for the improvements
range from mid-1992 through mid-1993.
   Those programs, along with a previously announced $40
million investment at Timken's Latrobe specialty steel unit,
make up the bulk of the planned spending for steel plant
improvements, Timken said. When completed, they will make
Timken competitive globally in alloy and specialty steels,
both in quality and cost, the company said.
   The largest part of Timken's $1 billion investment will be
for bearings plants, but the major bearings projects haven't
been announced. The company has announced plans for building
a $23 million bearings plant in Altavista, Va., and an
investment of $13 million to modernize production of large
bearings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
